{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777747105355,"sessionID":"ses_216060a9cffexhkFr5DZTait0t","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"task","callID":"call_00_Ph7UWN5LYsXFkmHzqS328971","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"description":"Explore prior experiments","prompt":"Read the file cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl and report the last 10 lines. Also check if cores/bench/LESSONS.md exists and read it if so. Also read the schemas/hypothesis.schema.json file to understand the exact schema requirements for hypothesis YAML files.","subagent_type":"explore"},"output":"task_id: ses_216046c1cffeg7f3VxcOoDau3t (for resuming to continue this task if needed)\n\n<task_result>\nHere are my findings across all three requests:\n\n---\n\n## 1. `cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl` — Last 10 Lines\n\nThe file contains only **1 line** total (a single JSON record):\n\n```json\n{\n  \"id\": \"baseline-bench-a3930e2\",\n  \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\",\n  \"category\": \"micro_opt\",\n  \"outcome\": \"improvement\",\n  \"fitness\": 301.04,\n  \"delta_pct\": 0.0,\n  \"vs_baseline\": 0.0,\n  \"fmax_mhz\": 135.21,\n  \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06,\n  \"cycles\": 4491485,\n  \"iterations\": 10,\n  \"lut4\": 9880,\n  \"ff\": 1858,\n  \"seeds\": [121.29, 135.21, 136.07],\n  \"formal_passed\": true,\n  \"cosim_passed\": true,\n  \"error\": null,\n  \"implementation_notes\": \"\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-02T18:35:51.802352Z\",\n  \"round_id\": 0,\n  \"slot\": 0\n}\n```\n\nKey observations:\n- This is a **baseline run** (`round_id: 0`, `slot: 0`), not an experiment.\n- **Fitness:** 301.04 (the baseline score).\n- **Formal and cosim both passed.**\n- **IPC** is near-zero (`2e-06`), which is suspicious — likely a CoreMark measurement artifact rather than real IPC, or the IPC field is used differently here.\n\n---\n\n## 2. `cores/bench/LESSONS.md`\n\n**Does not exist.** No file matching that path was found anywhere under the workspace.\n\n---\n\n## 3. `schemas/hypothesis.schema.json` — Schema Summary\n\nThe schema defines the required structure for hypothesis YAML files. Key rules:\n\n| Field | Requirement |\n|-------|-------------|\n| **`id`** | String matching regex `^hyp-[0-9]{8}-[0-9]{3}(-r[0-9]+s[0-9]+)?$` (e.g. `hyp-20260502-001-r1s0`) |\n| **`title`** | String, minimum 5 characters |\n| **`category`** | One of: `micro_opt`, `structural`, `extension`, `predictor`, `memory` |\n| **`motivation`** | String, minimum 20 characters |\n| **`hypothesis`** | String, minimum 20 characters |\n| **`expected_impact`** | Object with two required fields: |\n|   - `fitness_delta_pct` | Integer (expected % fitness change) |\n|   - `confidence` | One of: `low`, `medium`, `high` |\n| **`changes`** | Array (min 1 item), each entry has: |\n|   - `file` | String matching `^(rtl/[^.].*\\|test/test_[^/]+\\.py)$` — must be under `rtl/` (any extension, dotfile excluded) or a cocotb test file (`test/test_*.py`). Anything else is rejected at runtime. |\n|   - `description` | String describing the change |\n\nAll top-level fields (`id`, `title`, `category`, `motivation`, `hypothesis`, `expected_impact`, `changes`) are **required**.\n</task_result>","metadata":{"sessionId":"ses_216046c1cffeg7f3VxcOoDau3t","model":{"modelID":"deepseek-v4-pro","providerID":"opencode-go"},"truncated":false},"title":"Explore prior experiments","time":{"start":1777747071980,"end":1777747105355}},"id":"prt_de9fb86c70018vDR50v9rxVSjk","sessionID":"ses_216060a9cffexhkFr5DZTait0t","messageID":"msg_de9f9f5ac001EQoP27zYJ74vPX"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777747584170,"sessionID":"ses_216060a9cffexhkFr5DZTait0t","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"task","callID":"call_01_BHy09y7QFiXe5he2DcdB2446","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"description":"Analyze pipeline critical path","prompt":"I'm analyzing the RV32IM CPU in cores/bench/rtl/ for structural improvements. Read all the RTL files and identify:\n\n1. The critical path through the pipeline — which stage likely determines Fmax\n2. Where branches are resolved and the exact penalty (in cycles) for taken branches\n3. How forwarding works and what datapath components are in each stage\n4. Whether the MUL/DIV combinational paths are a concern for timing\n5. Read cores/bench/core.yaml for current metrics\n\nReport back with detailed findings about the pipeline structure.","subagent_type":"explore"},"output":"task_id: ses_2160455f2ffevN1yd46WNIcynO (for resuming to continue this task if needed)\n\n<task_result>\nNow I have all the information needed. Here is my comprehensive analysis:\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Pipeline Structure Analysis: `cores/bench/rtl/`\n\n### 1. Pipeline Overview\n\nThis is a **classical 5-stage in-order RV32IM core** (MIPS-style):\n\n```\nIF ──→ ID ──→ EX ──→ MEM ──→ WB\n```\n\n**Key architectural trait**: There is **no IF/ID pipeline register**. The IF stage output is purely combinational (`if_id_t` is resolved combinationally from the PC register and IMEM data). The ID/EX register is the first pipeline flop boundary, absorbing both the instruction fetch and decode into a single clock cycle. This means the combinational path in a single clock cycle is: **PC → IMEM address → external BRAM read → decoder → regfile read → ID/EX capture**.\n\n| Stage | Module | Latency | Key Datapath |\n|-------|--------|---------|-------------|\n| IF | `if_stage.sv` | Comb. output | PC register, +4 adder, redirect MUX, NOP injector |\n| ID | `id_stage.sv` | 1 cycle (ID/EX reg) | `decoder.sv`, `imm_gen.sv`, `reg_file.sv` (2R/1W), ID/EX register |\n| EX | `ex_stage.sv` | 1 cycle (EX/MEM reg) | Forwarding MUXes (2x 3:1), operand selection MUXes, `alu.sv`, branch comparator (6-way), redirect logic, EX/MEM register |\n| MEM | `mem_stage.sv` | 1 cycle (MEM/WB reg) | Store-data replicator, byte-mask generator, load-data extractor (shift+sign/zero extend), misalignment checker, MEM/WB register |\n| WB | `wb_stage.sv` | Comb. | 2:1 MUX (ALU result vs load data), drives regfile write port |\n\n**Retirement point**: Instruction retires when it reaches the MEM/WB register and `mem_wb_w.valid = 1`. RVFI is driven directly from the MEM/WB register contents plus the WB-stage write-data mux output.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Critical Path and Fmax Bottleneck\n\nThere are **two major combinational paths** competing for Fmax:\n\n#### Path A: IF→ID (single-cycle instruction fetch + decode)\n```\nPC register → imemAddr → (external BRAM) → imemData → decoder → imm_gen → regfile read → ID/EX setup\n```\nThis path includes external BRAM access latency. At 135 MHz (7.4 ns period), this is tight but achievable with fast FPGA BRAM (~2-3 ns access).\n\n#### Path B: EX stage (THE critical path)\n```\nID/EX register → forward_unit comparators → forwarding MUX (3:1 x 32-bit)\n              → operand MUX (2:1 x 32-bit)\n              → ALU combinational cloud (ADD/SUB/logic/shifts + THREE 32×32→64 multiplies + 32-bit signed/unsigned DIV/REM)\n              → result MUX\n              → branch comparator (32-bit signed/unsigned equality/magnitude)\n              → redirect logic + misalignment check\n              → EX/MEM setup\n```\n\n**Path B is the dominant timing bottleneck.** The culprit is the **fully combinational ALU** in `alu.sv` (lines 36-97). Every cycle, the ALU speculatively computes **all three multiply products** (`mul_ss`, `mul_uu`, `mul_su` — 32×32→64 bit) **and** the divider/remainder paths (`/` and `%`), plus all base RV32I operations (ADD, SUB, shifts, logic), then a final 19-way MUX selects the result. This is a massive combinational cloud sitting in the EX stage.\n\nThe evidence from `core.yaml` confirms the timing is marginal:\n```yaml\ncurrent:\n  fmax_mhz: 135.21    # barely above target of 135\n  lut4: 9880          # 98.8% of 10000 available\n  ff: 1858\n```\n\nThe LUT utilization at 98.8% and fmax just barely above target indicates the combinational cloud is pushing both resource and timing limits.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Branch Resolution and Penalty\n\nBranches are resolved in the **EX stage** (stage 3 of 5). The resolution path is:\n\n1. **Forwarded operands** (`rs1`, `rs2`) are obtained from the forwarding muxes (values from ID/EX regfile read, EX/MEM ALU result, or MEM/WB write-data).\n2. **Branch condition** is computed by a 6-way comparator (`ex_stage.sv` lines 72-80): BEQ, BNE, BLT, BGE, BLTU, BGEU — all in parallel.\n3. **`branch_taken`** = `is_branch && branch_cond` (line 81).\n4. **`branch_target`** = `pc + imm` (computed by a dedicated adder, line 82).\n5. **`redirect`** fires combinationally = `(branch_taken || is_jump) && !misalign_fault` (line 112).\n6. `redirect` feeds back to the IF stage to update PC at the next posedge, and to the hazard unit to generate `flush_if` and `flush_id`.\n\n#### Taken branch penalty: **2 cycles** (2 instruction slots wasted)\n\nTrace of a taken branch at PC=0x100, target=T:\n\n| Cycle | PC (start) | IF combo output | ID/EX content | EX/MEM content | MEM/WB content | Action |\n|-------|-----------|-----------------|---------------|----------------|----------------|--------|\n| t | 0x100 | B (valid) | prev_inst | older | oldest | B captured in ID/EX at end |\n| t+1 | 0x104 | I1→NOP (flush_if=1) | B | prev | older | **redirect=1**. ID/EX→'0, EX/MEM→B, PC→T at posedge |\n| t+2 | T | T (valid) | '0 (bubble) | B | prev | Target fetched |\n| t+3 | T+4 | T+4 | T | '0 (bubble) | B | **B RETIRES** |\n| t+4 | T+8 | T+8 | T+4 | T | '0 (bubble) | bubble retirement (invalid) |\n| t+5 | T+12 | T+12 | T+8 | T+4 | T | **T RETIRES** |\n\n- B retires at cycle t+3; T retires at cycle t+5.\n- Without branch: I1 would retire at t+4, I2 at t+5.\n- So the 2 cycles between B and T are occupied by a bubble from the flushed I1 slot and a bubble from the lost fetch slot — **2 wasted instruction slots**.\n\nThe design also includes **misaligned branch/jump target trapping** (`ex_stage.sv` lines 90-113). If a taken branch or jump targets a non-word-aligned address, `is_illegal` is forced, `reg_write` is suppressed, and the redirect is gated off (PC stays linear). This matches the RV32I spec (no C extension → all instructions must be 4-byte aligned).\n\n---\n\n### 4. Forwarding System\n\nForwarding is handled by `forward_unit.sv` and implemented in `ex_stage.sv`. It covers **both EX→EX and MEM→EX hazards** in hardware, leaving only **load-use** as the sole stall-inducing hazard.\n\n#### Forwarding sources (priority-ordered):\n\n| Select | Name | Source | When active |\n|--------|------|--------|-------------|\n| `2'd1` | EX_MEM | `ex_mem_w.alu_result` | EX/MEM register holds an instruction that writes rd ≠ x0, and rd matches EX-stage's rs1 or rs2 |\n| `2'd2` | MEM_WB | `wb_w_data` (WB-stage write-data mux output) | MEM/WB register holds an instruction that writes rd ≠ x0, and rd matches — but only if EX/MEM didn't already match |\n| `2'd0` | NONE | `id_ex_w.rs1_val` / `id_ex_w.rs2_val` (raw regfile read) | No hazard |\n\nPriority rule: EX/MEM > MEM/WB > none (the younger producer wins).\n\nThe `forward_unit` (`forward_unit.sv` lines 26-36) performs two independent 5-bit equality checks for each source register, comparing against `ex_mem_rd` and `mem_wb_rd`. The logic is:\n```\nif (ex_mem_w_en && ex_mem_rd != 0 && ex_mem_rd == rs)     → forward from EX/MEM\nelse if (mem_wb_w_en && mem_wb_rd != 0 && mem_wb_rd == rs) → forward from MEM/WB\nelse                                                        → use regfile value\n```\n\nIn the EX stage, the forwarded operands are selected via 3:1 MUXes (`ex_stage.sv` lines 34-43):\n```systemverilog\ncase (fwd_rs1_sel)\n  2'd1: rs1 = fwd_ex_mem;   // EX/MEM ALU result\n  2'd2: rs1 = fwd_mem_wb;   // WB write-data mux\n  default: rs1 = in.rs1_val; // raw regfile read\nendcase\n```\n\nAdditionally, the **regfile itself** has a write-first bypass (`reg_file.sv` lines 42-56). If the WB stage writes register xN in the same cycle that the ID stage reads xN, the read port returns `w_data` directly rather than the stale stored value. This covers the WB→ID forwarding edge case without an extra forwarding mux.\n\n#### Load-use hazard (the only stall):\n\nDetected by `hazard_unit.sv` (line 48-50):\n```\nload_use_hazard = id_ex_mem_read\n               && (id_ex_rd == if_id_rs1 || id_ex_rd == if_id_rs2)\n               && (id_ex_rd != 5'b0);\n```\nA LOAD in the EX stage produces its data only after the MEM stage. An instruction immediately behind that consumes the LOAD's destination register is stalled **for exactly 1 cycle**: `stall_if = 1`, `stall_id = 1`, `flush_id = 1` (the ID/EX register captures '0 — a bubble — while the IF/ID payload is held).\n\n---\n\n### 5. MUL/DIV Combinational Paths — Timing Concern\n\nThe M-extension arithmetic in `alu.sv` is implemented as **fully combinational logic**:\n\n- **Three multiply products computed in parallel every cycle** (lines 39-41):\n  - `mul_ss`: signed × signed (for MULH)\n  - `mul_uu`: unsigned × unsigned (for MUL, MULHU)\n  - `mul_su`: signed × unsigned (for MULHSU)\n  \n- **Four divide/remainder operations available in parallel** (lines 76-93):\n  - `DIV`: signed division with by-zero and overflow handling\n  - `DIVU`: unsigned division with by-zero handling\n  - `REM`: signed remainder with by-zero and overflow handling\n  - `REMU`: unsigned remainder with by-zero handling\n\n**This is a serious timing concern for several reasons:**\n\n1. **Multipliers**: Each 32×32→64 multiply maps to 4 Gowin DSP blocks (18×18 multiply-accumulate). While DSP blocks are fast (hardened), there are **three** independent multipliers competing for DSP resources. That's ~12 DSP blocks potentially active simultaneously, and the DSP cascade routing between blocks adds delay.\n\n2. **Dividers**: The 32-bit combinational divider (`$signed(a) / $signed(b)` in `always_comb`) has NO hardened support on the Gowin GW2A-18C. The synthesis tool must implement it in LUT fabric, typically as a non-restoring divider with ~32 stages of 1-bit subtract/shift/select. Each stage is ~2-3 LUT levels deep, for a total of **64-96 LUT levels**. At reference LUT delays (~0.5-1.0 ns per level), this path alone could consume 32-96 ns — far exceeding the 7.4 ns clock period at 135 MHz.\n\n3. **The `always_comb` constraint**: Because all M-extension operations are inside one `always_comb` block, the synthesis tool cannot legally pipeline the divider unless it performs aggressive retiming (which some tools do, but it's tool-dependent). The entire block must appear combinational.\n\n4. **Evidence of the problem**: The `targets.coremark_per_mhz` in `core.yaml` is 2.2, but `current.coremark_per_mhz` is **0.0**. The `current.coremark_iter_s` is `2.0e-06` (essentially zero). The experiment log shows 10 iterations completed in 4,491,485 cycles but IPC of `2e-06`. This suggests the CoreMark benchmark is either not running correctly or the metric computation has issues — but it also points to potential timing problems at the reported fmax.\n\n5. **The ALTOPS workaround**: Under `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` (used for formal verification), all M-extension ops are replaced with simple XOR-of-add/sub formulas. This sidesteps the SMT solver complexity but also **hides the real timing characteristics** of the divider from formal analysis. The real hardware path is only tested in FPGA deployment and cosimulation.\n\n**Mitigating factors**: CoreMark's compiled binary likely contains few or no M-extension instructions, so the divider path may not be exercised in the benchmark workload. However, static timing analysis considers ALL paths — the divider's combinational depth still determines the theoretical Fmax, even if functionally the divider is rarely used. The fact that Fmax=135.21 was achieved suggests either:\n- The synthesis tool does some clever optimization of the divider\n- The timing analysis relaxes false paths through the divider\n- The Gowin DSP blocks absorb some of the multiply timing\n\nBut the near-100% LUT utilization (9880/10000) strongly suggests the logic cloud is at its physical limit. **Any additional logic in the EX stage — including pipeline widening (dual-issue), better branch prediction, or additional forwarding paths — would likely fail timing closure without first addressing the combinational divider.**\n\n---\n\n### 6. Summary of Current Metrics (`core.yaml`)\n\n| Metric | Target | Current | Status |\n|--------|--------|---------|--------|\n| `fmax_mhz` | 135 | 135.21 | Barely passing (+0.15%) |\n| `lut4` | 10000 | 9880 | 98.8% utilized |\n| `ff` | — | 1858 | — |\n| `coremark_iter_s` | 300 | 2.0e-06 | **Failing** (benchmark not running correctly) |\n| `coremark_per_mhz` | 2.2 | 0.0 | **Failing** |\n\nThe baseline experiment (`log.jsonl` line 1) confirms: 4.49M cycles for 10 iterations with essentially zero IPC, indicating a functional problem with the CoreMark workload execution on this pipeline.\n\n---\n\n### 7. Structural Improvement Opportunities\n\n1. **Pipeline the ALU (especially DIV/REM)**: The single biggest timing win. Move M-extension ops to a multi-cycle or pipelined execution unit. This would dramatically reduce the EX-stage combinational depth and free up LUT resources.\n\n2. **Add an IF/ID pipeline register**: Currently the entire fetch→decode→regfile-read path is a single-cycle combinational cloud. Splitting it with an IF/ID register would reduce the per-cycle combinational depth (at the cost of one extra cycle of branch penalty and load-use latency).\n\n3. **Branch prediction**: A simple static predictor (backward-taken-forward-not-taken) or a small BTB could reduce the 2-cycle taken-branch penalty. The current design has no prediction — every branch is resolved in EX with a full 2-cycle flush.\n\n4. **Dual-issue potential**: The NRET=2 RVFI contract is already in place. Structurally, the register file has 2 read ports (matching dual-issue needs), and the forwarding paths already handle two sources. But the ALU is a single monolithic unit — dual-issue would require either duplicating the ALU or splitting it into separate integer and M-extension pipelines.\n\n5. **Forwarding optimization**: The current forwarding uses simple 5-bit equality comparators. For a wider pipeline, CAM-based or scoreboard-based forwarding would be needed. But for single-issue, the current approach is fine.\n</task_result>","metadata":{"sessionId":"ses_2160455f2ffevN1yd46WNIcynO","model":{"modelID":"deepseek-v4-pro","providerID":"opencode-go"},"truncated":false},"title":"Analyze pipeline critical path","time":{"start":1777747077649,"end":1777747584169}},"id":"prt_de9fb952b001DujUdS3DlmG2lX","sessionID":"ses_216060a9cffexhkFr5DZTait0t","messageID":"msg_de9f9f5ac001EQoP27zYJ74vPX"}}
